Recall that $a^m\div a^n=a^{m-n}$ for positive integers $m>n$ and $a^m\cdot a^n=a^{m+n}$. Now we can write $5^5\div5^4-5^3+5^2\cdot5^1$ as $5^1-5^3+5^3$. Using the definition of subtraction and the associative property of addition, we get \begin{align*}
5^1-5^3+5^3&=5^1+-5^3+5^3\\
&=5^1+(-5^3+5^3)\\
&=5^1+0\\
&=\boxed{5}.
\end{align*}

Since $\cot^{-1} \left( \frac{1}{x} \right) = \tan^{-1} x$ for all $x,$ we can write
\[\sin \left( 2 \tan^{-1} x \right) = \frac{1}{3}.\]Let $\theta = \tan^{-1} x,$ so $x = \tan \theta.$  Also, $\sin 2 \theta = \frac{1}{3},$ so
\[2 \sin \theta \cos \theta = \frac{1}{3}.\]Construct a right triangle with legs 1 and $x.$  Then the angle opposite the side length $x$ be $\theta.$

[asy]
